  "faq_items": [
    {
      "q": "Does weathered-wood asphalt actually look like real cedar shake?",
      "a": "From street distance, yes. Up close the difference is obvious -- asphalt is flat, cedar is dimensional. But at curb distance most observers cannot tell the two apart, and the asphalt option costs roughly one-fifth as much installed and carries a 30 to 50 year warranty versus 20 to 30 for cedar."
    },
    {
      "q": "How does weathered-wood pair with beige siding?",
      "a": "Generally well. The multi-tone roof gives the elevation visual texture that solid-painted beige siding by itself can lack. Best paired with at least one natural-material accent (stone, cedar, copper) so the multi-tone roof has a tonal anchor below it."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will weathered-wood fade like brown shingles do?",
      "a": "Less visibly. Brown shingles drift slightly cooler and slightly desaturated over 10 to 15 years. Weathered-wood blends already contain several shades, so any individual-shade drift is masked by the other granules in the blend. The visual age curve is gentler. Source: NRCA Asphalt Shingle Manual."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is weathered-wood appropriate for a modern home?",
      "a": "Less than for traditional architecture. Weathered-wood reads as 'aged' and 'natural' by design, which can fight the clean lines of a contemporary build. On modern farmhouse it can work; on stark contemporary it usually reads as out of place. Charcoal or black serves modern architecture better."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will weathered-wood show algae streaks in Florida?",
      "a": "Less visibly than gray or charcoal. The multi-tone blend hides the dark vertical streaks that Gloeocapsa magma algae causes on solid-gray shingles. All recommended SKUs include copper- or zinc-infused granules that inhibit algae growth in the first place. Source: NRCA Algae Discoloration field guidance."
    }
  ],
